{
  "text": "Clinically, P. knowlesi can be difficult to diagnose [CITATION_1] . Timely diagnosis and treatment are crucial for reducing the risk of malaria complications [CITATION_2] . For this reason, accurate identification of Plasmodium species is fundamental for proper clinical management and control strategies. Plasmodium species infections are typically diagnosed by microscopic examination of stained blood films, but there are limitations in sensitivity and specificity [CITATION_3] . Although there are newer techniques, manual microscopic examination of peripheral blood smears by thick and thin film is \"the gold standard\" for malaria diagnosis and species identification [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The thick film should be used for the detection of malaria parasites and the thin film for identification of species. All malaria films should be examined by 2 trained observers simultaneously or subsequently. During microscopy, a minimum of 200 oil immersion fields ( \u00d7 100 objective) should be examined in the thick film. This procedure takes about 10 min for an experienced observer, but longer for those who not often examine films containing malaria parasites [CITATION_6] . The specific changes of the shape of the occupied erythrocytes, presence of some characteristic dots (Sch\u00fcff-ner's dots, Maurer's clefts, and Ziemann's strippling) and the different morphology of the parasites in the life-cycle-stages are the basis of identification of malaria species during microscopic examination (Fig. 2) [CITATION_7] .",
